‚≠êÔ∏è Grades Pre K-5 ‚≠êÔ∏è
‚Ä¢ School opens at 8:50am and begins dismissal at 3:20pm M-F

‚Ä¢ School opens at 7:50am and begins dismissal at 2:12pm M-TH

‚Ä¢ 6-12 Drop-off will begin at 7:50am. More details to follow.
‚Ä¢ 6-12 pick up will begin at 2:15pm. More details to follow
‚Ä¢ Students driving will begin to enter the school at approximately 7:55am. More details to follow.

üêÆ Free Milk Drive Through Event ü•õ

The American Dairy Association North East is working with Dairy Farmers of America, Glazier Packing Company, and community partners to facilitate the distribution of more than 2,000 gallons of milk and 32,000 pounds of additional food through a local drive-thru event. There will be 800 boxes each of produce and additional dairy items, each containing 20 pounds of products.

WHERE/WHEN:
Saratoga County Fairgrounds (162 Prospect St., Ballston Spa, N.Y. 12020) on Wednesday, July 22, 2020 beginning at 11 a.m. Enter through Gate 1.

Each vehicle will receive two gallons of milk and one of each box, while supplies last.

post_text:
While the district reviews and analyzes the direction and guidelines from the state about what it will be required to do to safely and productively reopen, the district would like to gather thoughts from district families about the future delivery of education in Galway.

While the district will ultimately be required to implement the specific health and safety protocols issued by the state, it will have some local control about the delivery of education to students.

Please take this survey to let us know what you think about the delivery of education in Galway CSD. If you have multiple children in the district, please take this survey once per child to allow the district to gather information specific to grade levels.

https://forms.gle/YDkJUpTwLnM8pQgd7

The results of this survey will provide valuable insight for district administrators, teachers, and staff about how to best move forward in the fall. Thank you in advance for your participation. This survey will be open through Friday, July 31, 2020.

Many thanks to all the residents who voted in the 2020-21 School District Budget Vote and Board of Education election. After counting the absentee ballots, we are pleased to provide the following results:

Proposition 1: School Budget passed
Yes 1,016
No 502

Proposition 2: School Bus Purchase passed
Yes 1,039
No 462

Congratulations to Michelle Bombard and Karen English for being re-elected to the Board of Education for another four-year term of office.

post_text:
Dear Eagle Nation,
Joseph Henry Student Council wants to take the time to tell you how proud of you we are. This year has brought us many challenges and you all never gave up. You kept working even from home, you showed support for one another through kind messages and car parades, and our Galway Spirit held strong through pictures/videos on our Facebook page and District website.

You should all be very proud of yourselves and your accomplishments through this very challenging time. We hope to all be back together again in the Fall. Until then, stay safe, stay healthy and stay active. Have a great summer!

~JHE Student Council

post_text:
PLEASE READ this important information regarding the 2020-2021 Budget Vote and Board of Education Election.

School Budget Ballots will now be counted on Tuesday, June 16, 2020 beginning at 5 p.m.

Governor Cuomo's Executive Order 202.39 has modified the rules for the District Budget Vote and Board of Education election. Per the order, the District can only accept in-person ballots through 5pm on Tuesday, June 9, 2020. However, ballots delivered by mail will be counted as long as they are received by the district by 5 p.m. on Tuesday, June 16, 2020.

The Galway DoSomething Club is having a Positivity Contest for elementary students! They would like to spread positivity during this time with the help of elementary students! They encourage every elementary student to participate and have the chance to earn a prize.

üì∏ Parents, take a video or photo of your child(ren) doing something positive and email the video or photo to Rachel Germain at ragermain02@gmail.com.

Some positive activity ideas are:
üó£ Have your child(ren) write a positive quote or take a video of them saying a positive quote

üßµ Take a picture or video of your child(ren) helping the community, e.g. making masks

üòÅ Take a picture of your child(ren) smiling or anything else that can spread positivity.

The Positivity Contest will run from now until May 31, 2020

You can send multiple videos or photos of your child(ren). The Club will review all of the videos and photos that were entered and choose the most positive ones (one boy and one girl will win). üçÄ Good Luck!

post_text: Ms. Whalen's Wildlife and Natural Resources students made their own Paracord Survival Bracelets this week. Paracord bracelets are also known as survival bracelets or parachute cord bracelets and are considered a survival tool. The bracelets are worn by survivalists, hikers, climbers, campers, or anyone who enjoys the outdoors. These bracelets become extremely handy in survival or emergency situations. Didn't they turn out great?

Congratulations to Julia Reedy, who was accorded Highest Honorable Mention by PrepVolleyball in their 2019 "Soph 79" list of most impactful high school sophomores of 2019.

The PrepVolleyball website says Julia, "a three-year performer for the Golden Eagles...recorded 627 kills, 411 digs, 43 aces, and 27 blocks last fall. She was named League and Division MVP as well as First Team All-State Class D. She is a power hitter who impressed opposing coaches regularly."

Last month, Student Council was making announcements periodically to acknowledge some amazing women during Women's History Month. With the school closure, some students did not get their opportunity to announce. We would like to share them with you tonight and tomorrow night.

This announcement is from our Student Council President Kara Ferguson:

Today‚Äôs learning moment will be about the lovely Malala Yousafzai. She was born on July 19, 1997 in Mingora, Pakistan. She is still alive today at the age of 22. A group of terrorists called the Taliban were stopping all girls in her country from getting an Education. Malala won a Nobel Peace Prize for fighting against the Taliban. Many know Malala Yousafzai best for her involvement in women‚Äôs rights.

üì∑ Credit_Tess Thomas for Malala Fund

FUNDRAISERS will be in today!

Curb side pick up is available outside the elementary school cafeteria for ALL fundraisers, tomorrow, Thursday, March 26th from 8:00am-2:00pm.

The fundraisers will be on the tables outside the cafeteria with your child‚Äôs name on them. Please pull up and pick up from there. Due to COVID 19, no one will be available to load items into vehicles, to avoid any possible health risks.

Parents that are unable to pick up at this time, please let us know at galwaypsta@gmail.com.

We would like to thank Mrs. McDougall and Mr. Miller for monitoring this and helping us make this happen. This is a trying time for us all but as a community and school we are working together to come up with solutions and do what‚Äôs best to keep us healthy.

Thank you all for your orders!!

Galway Central School District conducted an unannounced lockdown drill at both the Elementary School and the Jr. Sr. High School. This was a drill to test the safety measures we have in place. The lockdown drill began at 11:45 a.m. and was lifted at 12:15 p.m. Everyone did an outstanding job and we are now back to our regular schedule.

If this were an actual emergency, we would ask that you refrain from calling or traveling to the school. Please be assured that the safety of our children is our number one priority. Thank you for your cooperation and patience.

post_text:
Ms. Whalen brought students to the NY Farm show in Syracuse, N.Y. There, the students got a chance to speak with representatives from different Agricultural Colleges like SUNY Cobleskill, SUNY Morrisville, University of Delaware.

They also were able to interact with representatives from different Agricultural companies such as Caterpillar, John Deere, Milwaukee Tool North America, STIHL, and Zoetis.

The students learned about tractor safety, solar panels, livestock nutrition, farm equipment, pesticides and chemicals, and were able to sit on different models of tractors. They came home with lots of goodies from the show!

‚Ä¢ No games will be scheduled for Mother‚Äôs Day, or Memorial Day Weekend.

Ms. Whalen's Small Animal Science class welcomed their 3rd furry visitor of the year for their unit on rabbits üê∞ üêà ü¶Æ

Students learned about Caspian, a Blue Dutch Rabbit, who is fully grown at 8-months old. They asked good questions about his living arrangements (inside vs. outside), habits (eating/chewing/playing with toys), and his breed/markings.

Do you think they'll be able to talk Mr. Miller into letting them adopt a bunny they met Ballston Spa Veterinary Clinic as a class pet???

Several Galway High School art students participated in the Liberty ARC‚Äôs Creative Expressions Art Show at The Century Club of Amsterdam, New York.

The exhibit featured artwork by Jack Ryan, Arianna Persaud, Hayli Raylinsky, Alex Malanoski, and Vanessa Colangelo.

As an added bonus, Arianna Persaud and Alex Malanoski each sold one of their pieces and may now consider themselves professional artists‚ÄºÔ∏è

The Art Department would like to thank Sharon Holbrook-Ryan for inviting the students to enter the show and transporting the artwork. We look forward to participating in the future.
